Let's just deal with this thing...
First the basics. To the right you can see the current status of
your active party members. It's just us three right now, but in
general the maximum amount of active party members is four. From this
area you can see our HP, MP, and TP.\n<Amber>
HP is our... Hit... Health... Points? Yeah, Health Points. As the
name suggests, it represents our "health." When the number hits "0"
that person falls unconscious. If everyone hits "0", it's impossible
to continue fighting. In other words...\n<Amber>
Tough crowd. Moving on we have MP. This represents a person's
current mana, which is used to cast magic. I'm the only one of
us that can use magic.\! For now..?\n<Amber>
Last of these is TP. This stands for "Technique Points." While
magic uses MP, techniques use TP. Techniques pretty much encompass
your physical attacks, with your sword, and your defensive techniques
While HP and MP don't normally regenerate on their own except
through rest, TP builds up while doing normal attacks. Just
normal sword swings, nothing special about them. Also, unlike HP
and MP, TP's max is always 100.\n<Amber>
Next, we have the actions you can take in battle. You two have
your normal "Attack" where you just swing your weapons. Below that
is "Skills." Both magic and techniques are considered skills.\n<Amber>
You have to "equip" skills before battles to be able to use
them during combat, and you can only equip up to four at a time.
None of us have more then four equippable skills right now, so
you don't have to worry about that.\n<Amber>
Next is "Guard." It lowers the damage taken until your next
turn. Some equippable skills and items can change your normal
guard into something else, like a taunt.\n<Amber>
You can also use items, change equipment, swap party members,
and, of course, run away from a fight.\n<Amber>
Now we'll focus on the rest of the battlefield. Up top we have
the turn order. Not everyone gets to act at the same time, so
instead the ones with the highest Agility stat go first.\n<Amber>
Over on the left you can see the current enemy. Unlike our
party members, we only have a general idea about their health;
no numbers for them! We also can't see their MP or TP at all.\n<Amber>
Below their health bar you can see a couple of symbols, right?
That shows an enemy's weakness. Of course, you need to first
discover the weakness before it shows up there, but that's as
simple as attacking it with the correct element.\n<Amber>
Not only will attacking an enemy with their weakness deal extra
damage, but it will also lower their "break shield" to the left.
